05360nam a22008295i 9780824857097DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248570977 a10.1515/97808248570972doi  a(DE-B1597)484576  a(OCoLC)1016764697  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aND1432.K6bK43 2015 7aART0350002bisacsh04a755/.99572231 aKendall, Laurel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGod Pictures in Korean Contexts :bThe Ownership and Meaning of Shaman Paintings /cJongsung Yang, Laurel Kendall, Yul Soo Yoon. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (184 p.) :b47 black & white images, 10 color images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Introduction: The Lives of Korean Shaman Paintings -- t2. What Are Shaman Paintings? -- t3. Korean Shaman Paintings Collected -- t4. Painted Gods at Home -- t5. Gods Painted, Gods Bought and Sold -- tCoda: Painted Gods in Museums -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShamans walking on knives, fairies riding on clouds, kings with dragon mounts: They are gods and they are paper images. Some are repulsed and unsettled by shaman paintings, some cannot stop collecting them, and some use them as sites of veneration. Laurel Kendall, Jongsung Yang, and Yul Soo Yoon explore what it is that makes a Korean shaman painting magical or sacred. How does a picture carry the trace of a god and can it ever be “just a painting” again? How have shaman paintings been revalued as art? Do artfulness and magic ever intersect? Does it matter, as a matter of market value, that the painting was once a sacred thing? Navigating the journey shaman paintings make from painters’ studios to shaman shrines to private collections and museums, the three authors deftly traverse the borderland between scholarly interests in the material dimension of religious practice and the circulation of art. Illustrated with sixty images in color and black and white, the book offers a new vantage point on “the social life of things.” This is not a story of a collecting West and a disposing rest; the primary collectors and commentators on Korean shaman paintings are South Koreans re-imagining their own past in light of their own modernist sensibility. It is a tale told with an awareness of both recent South Korean history and the problematic question of how the paintings are understood by different South Korean actors, most particularly the shamans and collectors who share a common language and sometimes meet face-to-face.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArt, ShamanisticxCollectors and collectingzKorea (South). 0aArt, ShamanisticzKorea. 0aPainting, KoreanxCollectors and collectingzKorea (South). 0aPainting, Korean. 7aART / Subjects & Themes / Religious.2bisacsh1 aYang, Jongsung, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aYoon, Yul Soo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311075236640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485709740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824857097423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824857097/original  a978-3-11-056413-